[1] Indonesia (East Nusa Tenggara)
Date: Sat 31 May 2008
Source: The Jakarta Post [edited]
<http://www.thejakartapost.com/node/170540>


At least 5 people have died and 58 are being
treated at Maumere General Hospital for dengue
fever in Sikka regency, East Nusa Tenggara.

The head of the disease control and environmental
health office in Sikka, Iskak Lafian Tori, said
Friday [30 May 2008] the epidemic has affected
Alok, East Alok, West Alok, Talibura, Lela,
Koting, Kewapante, and Kaegae districts.

"The epidemic has claimed at least 5 lives in the
past 2 months. We have deployed several teams to
carry out spraying in the affected districts and
to distribute free medicine to help relieve the
epidemic," he said.

He also called on locals to keep their
environment clean from the mosquitoes that spread
the virus and to avoid non-potable water.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[An interactive map of the Sikka district on East Nusa Tenggara,
Indonesia, can be accessed at
<http://www.maplandia.com/indonesia/nusa-tenggara-timur/sikka/oka/>. - Mod.TY]

******
[2] Indonesia (Java)
Date: Tue 27 May 2007
Source: The Jakarta Post [archives, subscription only, edited]
<http://old.thejakartapost.com/detailcity.asp?fileid=20080527.C10&irec=9>


A child, 7, a resident of Cakung, East Jakarta,
died Sunday [25 May 2008] after being
hospitalized for 3 days with dengue fever.

This child was the 2nd victim in the area this
year [2008], said Hairudin, an official in [the
child's] neighborhood, as quoted by
Beritajakarta.com.

He said he hoped the administration would conduct
fogging in his area to prevent further high
levels of breeding among _Aedes aegypti_
mosquitoes. "I expect them to act soon. We don't
want more victims," he said.

The East Jakarta health agency recorded 4762
people hospitalized with dengue fever in 2008.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Fogging is not an effective measure to control _Aedes aegypti_
populations and provide significant reduction of dengue virus
transmission. Elimination of the water catchments in which this
mosquito breeds is effective.

A map of Indonesia showing the location of Jakarta on Java can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/indonesia_pol98.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]

******
[3] Yemen
Date: Mon 2 Jun 2008
Source: Yemen News Agency (SABA) [edited]
<http://www.sabanews.net/en/news155727.htm>


Medical sources said on Monday [2 Jun 2008] the
number of people infected with dengue fever
amounted to more than 1000 cases in Shabwa
province, southeast of the Yemeni capital, Sana'a.

The sources were quoted by the independent
newsyemen.net as saying that the numbers of
dengue fever cases had increased remarkably in
some districts of the province.

The sources explained that field-spraying
processes are still continuous, pointing out that
the spraying campaign aims at eradicating
mosquitoes, which cause dengue fever.

Last week [26 May-1 Jun 2008], deputy director of
the Health bureau in Shabwa Ahmed Saeed said the
outbreak of the tropical epidemic has infected
more than 500 persons in the province during 2
days only.

Saeed voiced concern over the worsening health
conditions in Shabwa due to the proliferation of
dengue mosquitoes and the lack of health services
in order to combat the epidemic.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A map of Yemen showing the location of Shabwa can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/yemen_admin_2002.jpg>.
- Mod.TY]

