[4] Brazil (Rio de Janeiro)
Date: Thu 29 May 2008
Source: Reuters America Latina [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://lta.reuters.com/article/domesticNews/idLTAN2919450820080529>


The dengue epidemic, which has hit Rio de
Janeiro, the most lethal in the history of
Brazil, has caused 123 deaths so far this year
[2008], and the [health] authorities said that
they are investigating another 116 deaths which
are suspected to have been caused by the disease,
the [Health] Secretariat said.

Since January [2008], 162 701 dengue cases have
been reported in the state of Rio de Janeiro,
said the Secretariat of Health in a news release
issued Wednesday night [28 May 2008].

The most cases of [dengue] infection, 87 589, are
from the city of Rio, the major tourist
attraction in Brazil, which also leads with the
number of fatalities due to the disease, with a
total of 75.

In the state, 42 percent of the deaths occurred
in [children] less than 15 years of age, the
Secretariat said.

Dengue [virus] is transmitted by the _Aedes
aegypti_ mosquito, for which the hot and humid
climate of Rio provides good conditions for its
reproduction.

Although the current [dengue] epidemic is not the
one that has caused the most infections in
Brazil, it has had the highest mortality rate.
The greatest previous epidemic recorded in
Brazil, which also occurred in Rio de Janeiro,
was that of 2002 when 288 000 people were
infected and 91 died.

[Byline: Julio Villaverde]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-ESP
<promed@promedmail.org>

[An article published in Portuguese on 28 May 2008 in G1 Globo
<http://g1.globo.com:80/Noticias/Rio/0,,MUL582057-5606,00-MORTES+POR+DENGUE+PODEM+CHEGAR+A+NO+RIO.html>,
indicated that the greatest number of recorded dengue cases were
concentrated in the 15-49 year age cohort, with 54 percent of the cases.

A map of Brazil showing the states can be accessed at
<http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/americas/brazil.jpg>. - Mod.TY]

