[5] Brazil (Sergipe)
Date: Sun 25 May 2008
Source: Correio de Sergipe [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.correiodesergipe.com/lernoticia.php?noticia=27958>


While the tragedy of dengue in Sergipe starts to
show signs that this deadly disease is cooling,
the truth is that the numbers produced by it up
until now are horrifying.

There have been 20 174 reported [dengue] cases
and 8726 confirmations, per the numbers
officially released by the Secretariat of Health
of the state calculated as of 21 May [2008]. Also
in the month of April [2008], there were 13 266
dengue case notifications and 4780 confirmations,
resulting in an incidence of 652.4 cases per 100
000 population. May [2008], when there
has usually been a decline in the number of [dengue]
cases, also had alarming figures: there have been
2404 reported [dengue cases] and 1262 confirmed
[cases], for an incidence of 118.2 [dengue cases]
per 100 000 population.

These [data] are taking into account only the
1st 21 days of the month. As for DHF (dengue
hemorrhagic fever) cases, 119 have been
confirmed. There have been 334 cases of dengue
with complications confirmed throughout the State.

Last week, with the possibility of 3 more deaths
directly related to the illness, Sergipe has
taken over 1st place in the [fatality] ranking,
now that it proportionately [per unit of
population], has had more dengue deaths in 2008.
According to official figures of the state
Secretariat of Health, already there have been 21
confirmed [dengue] deaths and another 17 are
under investigation.

If one takes just the number of officially
confirmed dengue deaths, Sergipe is in 1st place
for this calamity; by dividing the 21 cases by
the total number of Sergipe's inhabitants, we
have 1.08 deaths per 100 000 inhabitants. And if
there is confirmation of cases under
investigation, the [incidence] reaches 2.11
deaths per 100 000 inhabitants.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[All eyes are turned to Rio de Janeiro, but the
higher incidence appears to have been Sergipe, at
least for incidence of deaths. However, there is
a known bias in the Brazilian dengue surveillance
system. DHF is underdiagnosed and reported, and
the result is this rather absurd situation of
more deaths than DHF [cases]. The WHO
classification is used, but few physicians are
able to use it correctly. - Mod.LJS

It is not only Brazil that has a problem with the
WHO definition of DHF -- other countries have
also complained that the WHO definition is not
appropriate to their circumstances. - Mod.JW]

******
[6] Guyana
Date: Fri 30 May 2008
Source: Caribbean Net News [edited]
<http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/news-8186--13-13--.html>


Guyana's Ministry of Health has called on
residents to remain alert as a result of 12
confirmed cases of dengue fever in region 9,
Lethem, close to the Guyana-Brazil border.

Health minister Dr Leslie Ramsammy said over the
past month there have been a number of reported
cases of fever in the region 9 area.

Over the last 4 weeks the Ministry has noted the
increase of reported fever cases from Region 9,
especially Lethem, and investigation revealed
that these cases were not due to malaria. A test
for dengue fever confirmed that some 12 cases
were the result of recent infection with the
dengue virus and were among persons in and around
Lethem, the minister said.

The minister added that cases occur sporadically
in Georgetown and all the coastal regions but
more so in the Lethem area of Region 9 and the
public has been advised that care must be taken
to avoid mosquito bites.

"The Ministry is recommending the use of mosquito
nets and, if possible, insecticide-treated nets
must be used, especially by pregnant women and
children under 5 years. Everyone should sleep
under a net" a release from the health ministry
outlined.

According to health officials, the use of insect
repellents can prevent mosquito bites if used as
recommended and residents are being urged to use
protective clothing, especially while being
outdoors at night, and to avoid dark colours
since they attract mosquitoes.

[Byline: Kevin Lindon]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

